  "response_text": "Creating a meal and fitness plan for someone living in a dorm with limited kitchen access can be a bit challenging, but it’s definitely doable! The key will be to focus on simple, nutritious meals that require minimal cooking and equipment, as well as an easy-to-follow fitness routine. Here’s a plan that can work well in such a situation:\n\n### Weekly Meal Plan\n\n**General Guidelines:**\n- Utilize a microwave, electric kettle, or hot plate if available.\n- Stock up on non-perishable items and easy-to-prepare foods.\n- Incorporate fresh fruits and vegetables whenever possible.\n- Hydrate with water and herbal teas.\n\n#### Breakfast Options (Choose one each day)\n1. Overnight oats (rolled oats, yogurt/milk, fruits, nuts/seeds)\n2. Greek yogurt with honey and granola\n3. Whole grain toast with peanut butter and banana\n4. Smoothie (using a blender: spinach, banana, yogurt/milk, protein powder)\n5. Instant oatmeal packets (choose low sugar options)\n\n#### Lunch Options (Choose one each day)\n1. Pre-packed salad mix with canned tuna or chickpeas\n2. Whole grain wrap with hummus, turkey, lettuce, and tomato\n3. Microwaveable quinoa or brown rice with steamed veggies (frozen)\n4. Canned soup (low sodium) with a piece of whole grain bread\n5. Rice cakes with avocado and cherry tomatoes\n\n#### Dinner Options (Choose one each day)\n1. Microwaveable brown rice or quinoa with canned beans and salsa\n2. Instant ramen with added spinach and an egg (cooked in microwave)\n3. Stir-fried frozen veggies with tofu or shrimp (quick cook in microwave)\n4. Baked potato (microwave) topped with black beans and cheese\n5. Couscous salad with cherry tomatoes, cucumber, and feta cheese\n\n#### Snacks (Choose as needed)\n- Fresh fruit (apples, bananas, oranges)\n- Nuts or trail mix\n- String cheese or cheese slices\n- Rice cakes with almond butter\n- Popcorn (microwaveable)\n\n### Weekly Fitness Plan\n\n**General Guidelines:**\n- Aim for at least 30 minutes of physical activity most days of the week.\n- Incorporate a mix of cardio, strength training, and flexibility exercises.\n- Use bodyweight exercises that can be done in a small space.\n\n#### Daily Workout Suggestions\n\n**Monday: Cardio**\n- 30 minutes of brisk walking or jogging in place\n- 10 minutes of jump rope (or simulated jump rope)\n\n**Tuesday: Strength Training (Upper Body)**\n- Push-ups (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n- Tricep dips on a chair (3 sets of 8-12 reps)\n- Plank shoulder taps (3 sets of 10-15 reps each side)\n\n**Wednesday: Cardio/Active Recovery**\n- 30 minutes of dancing or following an online dance workout\n\n**Thursday: Strength Training (Lower Body)**\n- Bodyweight squats (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n- Lunges (3 sets of 10-12 reps each leg)\n- Glute bridges (3 sets of 10-15 reps)\n\n**Friday: Core and Flexibility**\n- Plank (hold for 30-60 seconds, 3 sets)\n- Bicycle crunches (3 sets of 15-20 reps)\n- Stretching routine (15-20 minutes)\n\n**Saturday: Cardio**\n- Go for a longer walk or bike ride, or do an online HIIT workout (30 minutes)\n\n**Sunday: Rest and Active Recovery**\n- Light yoga or stretching (20-30 minutes)\n\n### Tips for Success\n- Plan your meals ahead and create a shopping list.\n- Prep any ingredients that require cutting or assembling ahead of time.\n- Stay flexible; if you can’t find a specific ingredient, swap it out for something similar.\n- Make the most of your dorm space by designating an area for workouts.\n\nFeel free to adjust this plan based on personal preferences, dietary restrictions, and available resources!",
